assigning unrelated bugs to this.

As of https://crrev.com/1204351, absl::optional is now a type alias

for std::optional. We should migrate toward it.

| cut -f1 -d: \

| grep \

git status

entry.title: Shared Storage: Tweak perf tests
entry.content:
We pare down the tracing done by the shared storage perf tests to the

minimum necessary and also add a max to the number of iterations of

a story action inside a story run. These tweaks are to prevent

running out of trace buffer space, particularly during the worklet

clear stories.



To offset the new cap on number of iterations, we set the default

pageset repeat to 10 (this is the number of times each whole story

runs). This number can be further increased by command line in order

to get a higher total count of histograms measured.



Also, we add a sleep at the end of each story run to give histograms

a chance to finish recording before the story is torn down.



Moreover, we simplify how the features t be enabled via command line

are presented, so it's easy to find and edit them in the future while

testing to see if a feature causes improvements or regressions.



Finally, we fix the DocumentClear story, as we forgot to renavigate

and hence refresh the database before each clear. So in particular,

for benchmarks other than shared_storage.fresh, the second through

last iterations of the action in the story wouldn't be equivalent to

the first.

entry.title: Include additional ZPS types in SBS' Total ZPS shown count.
entry.content:
The change ensures that the following suggestion subtypes are

accounted for when computing number of zero-prefix suggestions shown

when calculating the histogram grand total:



- Clipboard: Text, Url, Image,

- Most Visited Sites (incorrect provider type used for accounting).



The change intentionally does not include Verbatim Match: the

verbatim match is present in both prefixed- and zero-prefix contexts,

which makes it more complicated. Simply including ECHO suggestions

would always yield "1 ZPS shown", because we will always show a single

zero prefix suggestion. The benefits are slim and the risks are high,

making Verbatim Match an unlikely candidate to be included in the

Grand Total.



The change relocates subtype assignment for MV Tiles to the Provider.

This makes it also easier to properly test whether generated elements

have appropriate subtype annotation. The change expands existing test

coverage for the most visited sites provider to include subtype check

entry.title: [omnibox][ml] Update UrlScoringModelMappedSearchBlending for doc matches
entry.content:
When multiple URL suggestions have been assigned the same ML score, the

RunBatchUrlScoringModelMappedSearchBlending() function currently works

in such a way as to assign the same relevance score (via linear score

mapping) to all such suggestions (e.g. 0.017 --> 637). When constructing

the final set of matches to display to the user, this will result in

an arbitrary ordering of URL suggestions which often causes certain bad

candidate matches to be surfaced above good candidate matches in the

Omnibox. This bug is particularly obvious when dealing with remote

document suggestions, which don't have any local signals to help

generate distinct ML scores for each match.



In order to fix this quality issue, this CL adapts some of the

tie-breaking logic found in the other ML scoring variants to ensure that

no two URL suggestions are assigned the same relevance score. As such,

this fix will enable the Omnibox to prioritize showing more relevant

document suggestions over less relevant ones (by ordering them based

on legacy ranking when they have equal ML scores).



Furthermore, this CL also updates the behavior of DocumentProvider when

the relevant provider match limit params have been set.

entry.title: [DBSC] Treat offline state as any other connection error
entry.content:
BoundSessionCookieControllerImpl has some logic about monitoring the

offline state that affects:

1. cookie rotation requests, and

2. requests throttled due to expired cookie



For 2., there is no real downside to removing the offline logic.

The controller will quickly release requests deferred while offline

because the rotation request will fail without the network.



This change affects 1. as rotation requests will fail quickly without

the network instead of being delayed. This creates a difference when

Chrome goes back online.



To not make things worse, BoundSessionCookieControllerImpl keeps

observing the connection state changes and attempts to schedule a cookie

refresh whenever Chrome goes back online.

entry.title: [fuchsia] Add UrlLoaderThrottle to Dedicated Workers
entry.content:
Imported: https://crrev.com/c/5118582



Shared workers and Service workers are not currently supported, and

WebEngineContentBrowserClient::CreateURLLoaderThrottles() will not

create throttles.



For Dedicated Workers, we make the following code thread-safe in

WebEngineURLLoaderThrottleProvider::CreateThrottles():



```

content_renderer_client_

->GetWebEngineRenderFrameObserverForFrameToken(

local_frame_token.value())

->url_request_rules_receiver()

->GetCachedRules();

```



1. UrlRequestRulesReceiver::GetCachedRules() returns a

scoped_refptr, so UrlRequestRulesReceiver needs

to be alive during this chain, but is not needed after.



2. UrlRequestRulesReceiver is owned by the WebEngineRenderFrameObserver,

and WebEngineRenderFrameObserver::url_request_rules_receiver() returns a

pointer to it. So WebEngineRenderFrameObserver needs to be alive.



3. WebEngineURLLoaderThrottleProvider is created by

WebEngineContentRendererClient::CreateURLLoaderThrottleProvider() and

for Dedicated Workers, this is owned by

DedicatedOrSharedWorkerFetchContextImpl, which is created per-worker.



4. WebEngineContentRendererClient should outlive Dedicated Workers,

which are terminated by its owner Window. See

https://html.spec.whatwg.org/multipage/workers.html#the-worker's-lifetime

entry.title: Fix CHIPS for WebView when 3PCs are not enabled
entry.content:
If an Android developer disables 3PCs in their app, paritioned cookies

will not be returned. The root cause of this is that WebView uses its

own settings for cookies from the rest of Chromium.



The behaviour of Chromium is that partitioned cookies are still returned

when 3PCs are disabled so we are matching that.



Because permissions apply at the level of BrowserContext for the rest of

Chromium, we have to do an awkward work around here where we

optimistically retrieve all cookies, and then filter out the non

partitioned cookies. This is because we have no way of telling the lower

layers that this is the behaviour we want for _this_ WebView. There may

be a slight performance impact here but hopefully not a large one since

apps that have 3PCs disabled wouldn't be setting them in the first

place. The real issue is more around apps changing this setting at

runtime.

entry.title: NetworkChangeNotifierAutoDetect: cache current network state
entry.content:
This change factors out the connectivity manager API call from

NetworkChangeNotifierAutoDetect#getCurrentNetworkState() into a separate

method updateCurrentNetworkState(), which stores the result in

mNetworkState. getCurrentNetworkState() now just returns the current

value of mNetworkState.



All the callsites of getCurrentNetworkState() were updated to also call

updateCurrentNetworkState() beforehand, so the end result should be the

same as before.



This is a preparation change for https://crrev.com/c/5018956, where

unnecessary system calls will be eliminated by only calling

getCurrentNetworkState() where we know the state is sufficiently

up-to-date (currently planned to be limited to WebView startup).

entry.title: Reland "Lacros testing: Make browser init param overriding more robust"
entry.content:
This is a reland of commit e5f6f1434e631cd1c8154a41ee95ce6126688e9a.

The only difference is: disabling a test that conflicts with

the new implementation (see b/323984075).



Original change's description:

> Lacros testing: Make browser init param overriding more robust

>

> See chromium:1508245 for context.

>

> - Decide whether crosapi is enabled based on the command line

> switches. In particular, make it independent of when/whether

> BrowserTestBase::SetUp gets called.

> We still provide DisableCrosapiForTesting for legacy reasons,

> as some tests need to ovrerride it.

>

> - This, plus some new checks, make it hard for tests

> * to accidentally and silently override the Ash-provided init

> params with mostly empty ones, or

> * to accidentally and silently prevent the Ash-provided params

> from even being read.

>

> - Address a TODO in InProcessBrowserTest thanks to these changes.

>

> - Call DisableCrosapiForTesting in ViewsTestBase-derived tests that

> run with crosapi enabled but are not prepared to set it up (and thus

> would fail one of the new checks) and in fact don't need crosapi.

>

> - Remove InProcessBrowserTest::IsCrosapiEnabled() in favor of

> !chromeos::BrowserParamsProxy::IsCrosapiDisabledForTesting(). There

> is no need to have the InProcessBrowserTest predicate and it's not

> an InProcessBrowserTest level concept.

>

> - Remove ScopedDisableCrosapiForTesting class, as there is no need for

> a scope. Tests should either not call DisableCrosapiForTesting at

> all or should do it very early on (CHECK'd). Undoing it is not

> supported and it's not neceesary because tests run in separate

> processes.

>

> - Add documentation to startup/README.md.

>

> - Remove some uses of IsCrosapiDisabledForTesting from production code

> that are no longer needed.

>
